Ces villas continuent à nous émerveiller. Leurs infrastructures, l\'eau courante, la distribution de la chaleur, le tout-à-l\'égout, l\'intégration des espaces verts et même les formes des objets quotidiens sont d\'une modernité spectaculaire. Ce catalogue évoque une maison pompéienne dans ses pièces les plus connues et traditionnelles : l\'atrium, le triclinium, la culina, le péristyle autour du jardin, le balneum, le venereum. object_dating_comment.2: According to Franken, the bust of Mars is related to the steelyard. By the use of stylistic criteria, the bust is assumpted to be from late Republican to early Augustan period.
object_dating_comment.3: Motive of sliding-weight belonging to Roman imperial period
object_dating_comment.4: Dating of the hoard is differential (Monaco 1957, 247: reign of Hadrian / Kaufmann-Heinimann 1998, 294: 1st c. BCE to 1st c. CE / Feugère 2003, 28: end of 2nd c. BCE to mid of 1st c. BCE)
object_dating_comment.5: Dating of the hoard is differential (Monaco 1957, 247: reign of Hadrian / Kaufmann-Heinimann 1998, 294: 1st c. BCE to 1st c. CE / Feugère 2003, 28: end of 2nd c. BCE to mid of 1st c. BCE)
object_dating_comment.7: Based on the dating by Franken due to characteristic features of the balance although some stylistic criteria (if the sliding-weight belongs genuinely to the balance) point to a later date in the middle of the first century CE.
object_dating_comment.8: The inscription mentions the second consulate of Lucius Verus with Marcus Aurelius as his senior partner from 161 CE. Gauging inscription likely to have been applied only after balance had been in use for considerable period of time.
object_dating_comment.12: Gauging inscription of 47 CE. Cf. ID 0040.
object_dating_comment.28: Gauging inscription of 47 CE. Cf. ID 0020.
object_dating_comment.31: Based on stylistic criteria Franken dates the sliding weight to the Tiberian period, cf. ID 0046.
object_dating_comment.33: According to stylistic criteria, the bust is assumed (Franken) to date to Tiberian period, cf. ID 0044.
object_dating_comment.34: Grave offering together with coins of the 1st cent. CE.
object_dating_comment.35: Occupation time of roman fort from 120 to 260 CE.
object_dating_comment.36: Occupation time of roman fort from 120 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.37: Probably end of 1st to beginning of 2nd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.38: 2nd half of the 1st cent. CE to mid 3rd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.39: Found in layer together with pottery; pottery dates neronian to early flavian: 60-75 CE
object_dating_comment.51: Building sacrifice during the construction of the wooden fort about 90 CE (Grönke 1990, 10)
object_dating_comment.53: Dated by few associated finds to the 1st cent. CE (Mutz 1983, 35)
object_dating_comment.56: The Roman fort Osterburken existed from 160 CE to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.71: The bust (if it belongs genuinely to the steelyard) can be dated (based on stylistic criteria by Franken) around 550 CE
object_dating_comment.74: Franken (8NKC882F) dates the sliding-weight to late first early second century CE. The sliding-weight has a separate inventory number and possibly doesn’t belong to balance.
object_dating_comment.76: Bendeguz (in SIA34PXI) dates the balance to the 9th century CE based on a comperandum from Corinth from a secure context
object_dating_comment.81: The ship wreck is dated to the 6th or 7th century. The inscriptions are dated based on stylistic reasons to the 6th century.
object_dating_comment.86: Occupation time of roman fort from around 150 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.87: Hoard is dated 3rd to 4th cent. CE
object_dating_comment.88: Occupation time of roman fort from around 150 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.90: Terminus post quem by coins in hoard.
object_dating_comment.94: Hoard is dated to the 1st third of the 3rd cent. CE, burial of hoard around 233 CE
object_dating_comment.95: Occupancy of the Roman fort Stockstadt is dated from 100 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.96: Occupation time of roman fort from 110 to 270 CE
object_dating_comment.98: Well filled after fire disaster (Planck 1983, 153); timbers out of the filling of the well dated by dendrochronology; well could be filled only after 255 CE; abandonment of the vicus 260 CE (Planck 1983, 156)
object_dating_comment.101: Hoard is dated to the 1st third of the 3rd cent. CE, burial of hoard around 233 CE
object_dating_comment.121: The balance was part of the Hamilton collection. Hamilton formed his collection as British envoy to Naples between 1764 and 1798. The balance supposedly stems from the contemporary excavations of Pompeji or Herculaneum.
object_dating_comment.137: Latest coin dates 625/626 CE, ship foundered a few years later.
object_dating_comment.139: Dwelling inhabited from 5th to 6th cent. CE (Knific 1991, 21)
object_dating_comment.151: Latest coin dates 625/626 CE, ship foundered a few years later.
object_dating_comment.169: "found in Late Roman levels (5th-6th century A.D., lot BZ 1520)"
object_dating_comment.170: Dwelling inhabited from 3rd to 6th cent. CE (Knific 1979, 761-762)
object_dating_comment.171: Dwelling inhabited from 3rd to 6th cent. CE (Knific 1979, 761-762)
object_dating_comment.173: Utilisation period of workshop from the beginning of 2nd cent. to the beginning of 3rd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.188: Early to middle imperial period (ca. 50-276 CE). The gallo-roman vicus at Schwarzenacker was completely destroyed by the Alemanni in 276 CE.
object_dating_comment.189: Grave dated by the end of the fifth century.
object_dating_comment.190: Grave dated by first half of 5th cent.
object_dating_comment.204: Found within the filling of the space for firing of a pottery kiln; main working period of this pottery kiln: 2nd cent. CE; the pottery kiln and the whole pottery workshop was rendered at the end of 2nd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.206: Hoard is dated to the 1st third of the 3rd cent. CE, burial of hoard around 233 CE
object_dating_comment.219: Early byzantine, 1st half of 5th cent. CE
object_dating_comment.220: Dating of the hoard: 2nd to 4th cent. CE
object_dating_comment.224: Hoard from the middle of  3rd century CE (Alemanni invasions), possibly late.
object_dating_comment.225: Hoard from the middle of  3rd century CE (Alemanni invasions), possibly late.
object_dating_comment.230: Eldest grave of the so-called „Fürstengräber“ of the cemetery Gellep-East, dated around 530-550 CE.
object_dating_comment.233: Merowingerzeit / 5. - 7. Jahrhundert (möglicherweise handelt es sich aber auch um ältere Instrumente, die lange in Gebrauch blieben)
object_dating_comment.244: Found in the area of grounding of a production site, dating by findings to the beginning of the 1st cent. CE
object_dating_comment.245: The dating of the hoard by Feugère to the end of the 2nd cent. BCE is based upon the shapes of the bronze vessels by comparison with a hoard found at Parma. Possibly an indication for an earlier dating of the typ of Valle Ponti, but the bronze vessels from the  hoard found at Agde could have been used for a long time before being hoarded.
object_dating_comment.255: Occupation time of roman fort from 120 to 260 CE
object_dating_comment.257: Hoard is dated to the 1st third of the 3rd cent. CE, burial of hoard around 233 CE
object_dating_comment.278: Find context (hoard) dates to the 4th century CE, maybe to the end of the 4th century CE
object_dating_comment.279: Hoard dates 2nd half 4th cent. to 1st half 5th cent. CE (Bozic 2005, 356)
object_dating_comment.280: 2nd half of 4th century CE (Bass et al. 1971, 37)
object_dating_comment.284: Latest coin dates 625/626 CE, ship foundered a few years later
object_dating_comment.285: Existence of the Roman fort of Anreppen from 4 to 9 CE
object_dating_comment.286: Hoard is dated to the 6th cent. CE (Gaspari et al. 2000, 188), but Bozic disbelieves it and dates it from the middle of the 4th to the middle of the fifth cent. CE (Bozic 2005, 356)
object_dating_comment.288: Ship wreck is dated to mid of 1st cent. CE. According to Oleson the steelyard in not related to the wreck, however.
object_dating_comment.292: Dating of the find context is around 30 BCE to 280 CE
object_dating_comment.311: Found in an embankment which is dated before 2nd or 3rd century CE (dating of the last construction above the embankment)
object_dating_comment.312: Found within an ash layer of a roman villa; roman villa is dated 2nd half of 2nd cent. CE
object_dating_comment.314: Ship wreck is dated 1st half of 1st cent. BCE
object_dating_comment.315: Ship wreck is dated 1st cent. CE

object_dating_comment.317: Occupation time of roman fort from 120 to 260 CE

object_type_comment.7: The balnance shares most of the features characteristic of the balances of type Valle Ponti. Merely the scalearm-end is formed in the shape of a pine cone and not as a ring as it is typical for the balances of type Valle Ponti.
object_type_comment.46: The scale-arm of the balance compares to those of balances of type Pomppeii. However, the first component of the load-hanging differs from type Pompeii. The scale-plate was apparently attached  to this component by strings made from organic material. In the respect the balance resembles the balances of type Eining, which, however, are made from iron.  Compare object 0421.
object_type_comment.110: We assume that the load-hanging chain and hook are not original. In particular the hook is unusal for a load hook. In addition there are usally allways two load-hooks. Based on this assumption we attribute the balance to the type Walbrook.
object_type_comment.128: This steelyard shares all characteristic features of the balances of type Valle Ponti except for the ring at the scale-arm end. This object may be interpreted as evidencing the transition between types Valle Ponti and Pompeii
object_type_comment.215: The attribution to the type Pompeii is made based on the assumption that the weight attached to the load hanging does not originally belong to this balance.
object_type_comment.223: One of the few balances of type Walbrook, which are equipped with a scale-plate instead of an additional counterpoise as part of the load hanging.
object_type_comment.396: The balance mixes in rather unique fashion features characteristic for the types Pompeii and Osterburken. It for instance has the pinned eyelets characteristic for the balances of type Osterburken, but only two and not the usual three. Correspondingly it employs a single cast eyelet for the  load hanging, as do the balances of type Pompeii.
